  "text": "Note that the log L term comes from the region of integration ǫ/L 2 ≪τ ≪ 1 which, in the original variable, translates to ǫ ≪ τ ≪ L 2 . This is the infrared region and hence is not affected by the details of the ultraviolet cut-off ǫ, which only affects the contribution to the integral from the region τ ∼ ǫ. This is important since eleven dimensional supergravity is known to have ultra-violet divergences [CITATION_1] . The reader may nevertheless worry about the fact that the UV divergent terms could give contributions which dominate over the logarithmic corrections, e.g. a term involving a n will give a one loop contribution of order L d−2n . Thus for example, the a 0 term, if non-zero, would have produced a contribution of order L 11 in d = 11. To avoid this worry we could consider, instead of the free energy F , the quantity (Ld/dL − 1)(Ld/dL − 3) · · · (Ld/dL − 11)F . In this all polynomials in L up to order L 11 cancel, and the dominant term is proportional to log L, whose coefficient we are calculating. A similar trick was used in [CITATION_2] for extracting the universal part of entanglement entropy in quantum fleld theories.",
